{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"86b4638b-263a-419c-9673-795556801664","content":"The project doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what's needed. To publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org, add these properties to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for …</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <RepositoryUrl>https://github.com/you/repo</RepositoryUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nKey points:\n\n- **`PackAsTool`** — marks the project as a .NET tool.\n- **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI name users will invoke (e.g. `my-mcp-server`).\n- **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — tools must be console apps.\n\nThen pack and publish:\n\n```bash\ndotnet pack -c Release\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_NUGET_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\nUsers install with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\n```\n\nAnd configure it as an MCP server using stdio:\n\n```json\n{ \"command\": \"my-mcp-server\" }\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"66439765-be74-4102-a44b-f15790b5a4d5","outputTokens":448,"requestId":"F05A:F615C:126177A:14C3D50:69F941D1"},"id":"de43c90e-4eee-4d79-9249-b28ca9e52a3b","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:03:21.008Z","parentId":"91916f7d-510a-4397-ab45-c3b22a726924"}
